# Rust Tauri Commands

## Command signature

```rust
#[tauri::command]
async fn command_name(
    state: tauri::State<'_, AppState>,
    param: ParamType,
) -> Result<ReturnType, String> {
```

- Always `async`. Always `Result<T, String>`.
- Convert errors with `.map_err(|e| e.to_string())` — no `.unwrap()`, no `.expect()`.
- Register every new command in `main.rs` `.invoke_handler(tauri::generate_handler![...])`.

## State

- Shared state via `tauri::State<'_, T>` — never global statics.
- Wrap mutable state in `Arc<Mutex<T>>` or `Arc<RwLock<T>>`.
- Prefer `RwLock` for read-heavy state.

## Error handling

- Return `Err(string)` for recoverable errors, not panics.
- Use `?` operator inside commands to propagate errors cleanly.
- No `unwrap()` in command bodies. In tests, `unwrap()` is acceptable.

## File / IO

- All paths go through `tauri::api::path` resolvers — no hardcoded absolute paths.
- Use `tokio::fs` for async file ops inside async commands.

## New files

- One module = one file. Register in `mod.rs` or `main.rs`.
- Don't add `pub` to everything — only expose what the command surface needs.

## Refactoring constraints

- Never refactor more than one function group per response
- When splitting modules: show file structure first, await confirmation before writing code
- Max response size for refactoring: one new file or one function group
- Do not inline existing logic — move it as-is, refactor separately

## Documentation

- Public functions (`pub fn`, `pub async fn`): one-line `///` comment explaining
  the "why", not the "what". Keep it under 120 chars.
- Functions returning `Result`: add `# Errors` section describing when `Err` is returned.
- Private functions: no doc comments. Use a clear name instead.
- No `# Arguments` or `# Returns` sections — types are in the signature.
- Do not add doc comments during refactoring passes — separate commit only.
